So I just finished reading EAOS and I have a few thoughts. I haven’t been paying attention to any discussion of this story, so I apologize if some or most of this has already been talked about.

For starters, I love the concept. I held off on reading this for a long time because of personal shit, but the idea intrigued me. And the actual execution is pretty good, it’s a great mix between melancholy and upbeat that I think is realistic for the situation, for the most part. And the end to the most recent chapter was perfect! It’s the kind of cliffhanger that leaves me begging to read the next.

That said, I do have some problems with it. The syntax and grammar are all over the place, which I’m not too bothered by seeing as how we’re not professional writers so it doesn’t really matter in the long run, but sometimes it does get distracting. Especially the repetition.

There’s a lot of fat that can be trimmed off with little consequence. Like, a lot. I’m sure it was easier to digest with the chapters spread out, but I sometimes found myself outright skipping entire paragraphs because I just didn’t think any of it was relevant. The majority of what I glazed over could’ve been explained just fine with only a few sentences. This is apparent in, for example, most of the dream sequences, which drag on a lot more than they should, and are also WAY more lucid than dreams actually are. When you’re going through the revising phase, ask yourself,
>Is this scene really necessary?
>Will this scene or action affect the characters later on?
>Do I really need to put this much detail in this description?
>Do I need to mention this small movement this character makes?
Obviously some filler is okay, but too much of it can cause a scene to become a chore to read, even high-action ones.

>I tend to have this problem as well
>>41381348
>i just don't want to bother people for beta reading
The way I'm tackling this right now is to import my draft text (second in my case) into a word processor that lets me highlight text.
No highlighting is dialogue.
Red is for internal narration paragraphs.
Yellow is for action paragraphs.
Blue is for action tags within a dialogue paragraph.
Purple is for sensory outside of human norms, and green is for whatever issue I want to work on then.

It's kind of funny, but being able to look at my relative paragraph lengths for these types made me more conscious of when they could be combined or split for better readability.

If your chosen program doesn't give you stats on sentence count as well as paragraph count, copy your text into Grammarly. It's simple math to see if a given scene needs fat cut. Action scene? You shouldn't have a fifty paragraph action scene with three hundred sentences and 15k words total.
You know what your issues are. Use any tool you can get your hands on and do the exact opposite of your last writing editing stage.
Being forced to see it differently is a technique I learn long ago from artists. Works in music and writing as well.

And please, read your text out loud at some point. Not only will you sharpen your dialogue, but you might find out how your character talks. Most people have a really bad feel for the pace of text unless they're poets or musically inclined. Also helps with grammar & spelling.

Anonymous Sat 04 Sep 2021 02:29:09 No.41383123 Report
Quoted By: >>41383449 >>41383634
>>41382520
>Internal narratives are hard
Indirect free speech, my friend.
The trick with third person is learning to disconnect from your own thoughts for a bit. As a reader, I don't need what you think the character thought, I need you out of the way.
Think of it like a signal, whether digital or analog. Put too much in between the source and end, and it will be colored.

The moment of clarity I've used to teach complex processes is by having the person pick up a pencil and write their name.
Easy?
Now do it with your off hand, or upside down.
When you learn a tool, you think through it. Your brain doesn't need to say down and to the left as you write. You don't think A-n-o-n, or whole words.
So while reading helps you by showing you written communication, it requires many hours of doing it yourself to stop thinking of the issue. Like anything else, practice with intent.

>>41383919
It depends on the piece.
I usually write dialogue first, but I want enough down that I can (especially for longer pieces) go back weeks later and add whatever I didn't think of previously.
The whole purpose of a first draft is to get enough down that you learn what the story is. I go back all the time and add paragraphs or scenes, usually because I edit up. Other sessions I'm looking for redundancies.
To give you numbers, I have a first draft that was ~ 75k. Currently at ~ 100k, with about 25k more that got trimmed because I cut some flashbacks.

And like >>41384031 points out, sometimes telling is the right thing to do, same way we get told that active voice is good and passive isn't. If the passive voice is more concise and clear, use it. If you've already established in your worldbuilding three chapters back that the village's tech level is medieval, then you probably don't need to spend three pages glossing over what the thatched roofs look like right now.

First off, I wanna say, don’t take my word as gospel. I’m just one guy giving my opinion, and there are many others who likely disagree with me on certain aspects.

>Whenever I write up the chapter I constantly think I need to keep on expanded upon it further and further; my worry being that the pacing or storytelling might be too direct, boring, or barebones
I touched on this in another reply, but I—as well as many others—have this insecurity too, and all it takes is a beta reader to solve. Because you can’t understand your writing style and pacing by yourself, not even a grammar software can.

>I didn’t think that all that extra fluff I was throwing on was making it such a chore to read through.
Too much of a description can have the opposite of the intended effect. I remember one specific paragraph where you went into way too much detail about a gun. I get you like guns, but most of the time the specific details don’t need to be said, they can be implied! If I had to describe a box of Fruit Loops, I would just say, “it’s a mostly-red colorful box with a bird on it,” not go into extreme detail on all the little things that are on it. Oftentimes, a paragraph can sound a lot better in the mind of the author, but it can come off as confusing or hard to follow to the readers.

To keep this second part brief, the unnecessary scenes mostly include the slice of life, which started to become the repetitive after a while.
